story.text: One of the most desirable properties in queue or stream based systems is increased efficiency as the queue depth grows. Without that property, slight mode shifts can push the system into the state of perpetually growing backlog. [https://twitter.com/_joemag_/status/1511027555813318658 tweet]

Increasing resource unable to keep up with demand. A timeseries chart showing pieces of work per day with three lines: incoming pieces at about 15 per day, outgoing pieces at about 9 per day, and the backlog growing linearly over time without bound.

There are several patterns systems can use to gain that property. The simplest one is to shed load, for example by dropping the oldest events in the queue. As the backlog grows, the system sees less incoming work. That's pretty efficient!

But there are other patterns for when load shedding is not possible. Batching is great at increasing efficiency. By batching work in the presence of backlog, various overheads get amortized across larger number of requests. Overall efficiency goes up. That's good.

There are other, more sophisticated patterns too. For stream based systems, stream compaction is a powerful technique. Redundant and ephemeral events get compacted away, and the further behind a client falls, the more effective such compaction becomes.
The important fact is that without this property, backlogs can become a major risk for queue and stream based systems.
redundant and ephemeral are special cases in the class events I can ignore - having efficient content-based filtering pushed down into the infrastructure can be very helpful.

I also like systems with explicit backpressure, that refuse work when under load, and 'queue-with-cancellation' and 'queue-with-timeout' so that clients are not left with unbounded time to completion. Hidden failures in either durability or execution progress are anathema.
And scale up based on (shared) queue depth. When the checkout queue gets too long, open some more!

"In queueing theory, the behavior of queues when they are short is relatively uninteresting. After all, when a queue is short, everyone is happy. Its only when the queue is backlogged, when the line to an event goes out the door and around the corner,that people start thinking about throughput and prioritization." Avoiding insurmountable queue backlogs [https://aws.amazon.com/builders-library/avoiding-insurmountable-queue-backlogs/ link]
Time to lives on messages. If you have duplicate messages in that backlog sometimes caching values to avoid computing them helps you speed up as your backlog increases.

Funnily enough I literally just published an article about similar strategies (batching and deduping) for HTTP based systems where the queue is queued up HTTP requests on the event loop of a process handling many concurrent requests [https://nathanpeck.com/concurrency-deep-dive-strategies-for-high-traffic-applications/ link]

Batched writes example. Timeseries chart with three lines: incoming requests growing linearly, downstream API calls growing more slowly in stepped increments, and perceived latency diminishing over time.
